    "202": {
      "play": "QUEEN: Fie, you must give way.",
      "notes": [
        "Fye, you must giue way] As a rule, the majority of editors from CAPELL to the GLOBE ED. indicate a change of address by dashes.—CAPELL conformed rigidly to the rule. Indeed, I think, it originated with him. The Globe disregarded it, and the editors since 1864, who have used the Globe’s text to print from, likewise omit these dashes; notably R. G. White, who, in his First Ed. 1860, scrupulously retained them; in his second Ed., in 1883, discarded them. To use these dashes intelligently assuredly adds to editorial problems, as in the present instance. To whom is this ‘Fye’ addressed, to Cymbeline or to Imogen? and to"
      ]
    },
    "203": {
      "play": "[Enter Pisanio.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "204": {
      "play": "Here is your servant.—How now, sir? What news?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "205": {
      "play": "PISANIO: My lord your son drew on my master.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "206": {
      "play": "QUEEN: Ha?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "207": {
      "play": "No harm, I trust, is done?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "208": {
      "play": "PISANIO: There might have been,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "209": {
      "play": "But that my master rather played than fought",
      "notes": []
    },
    "210": {
      "play": "And had no help of anger. They were parted",
      "notes": [
        "no helpe of Anger] DOWDEN: So Sidney, Arcadia (Qto ed. 1590), p. 315, recto: ‘his Courage (vnused to such iniuries) desired helpe of Anger to make him this answere.’ So in Lear, III, vii, 79: ‘Nay, then, come on and take the chance of anger.’—CRAIG: If a man loses his temper in sword-play he gives himself away to his adversary. Shakespeare makes Mecænas (Ant. & Cleop., IV, i, 9) express this truth: ‘Never anger Made good guard for itself.’ Here it means, ‘Cloten’s brutal assault did not induce him to strike him in return, he merely stood on his guard.’ [Craig’s note seems to imply that anger would not have helped Posthumus, and that he parried Cloten’s blows, but gave none. We know, however, from the next scene that he drove Cloten back, which could hardly have been accomplished by passive parrying. Pisano says that Posthumus merely played with Cloten, and had not that vindictiveness that anger would have imparted.] Thus in Dowden’s excellent illustration, Amphiautus was in a state of passive melancholy and needed the ‘help of anger’ to rouse him to answer the challenge he had just received."
      ]
    },
    "211": {
      "play": "By gentlemen at hand.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "212": {
      "play": "QUEEN: I am very glad on ’t.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "213": {
      "play": "IMOGEN: Your son’s my father’s friend; he takes his part",
      "notes": []
    },
    "214": {
      "play": "To draw upon an exile. O, brave sir!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "215": {
      "play": "I would they were in Afric both together,",
      "notes": [
        "Affricke] FORSYTH, in a chapter on 'Parallelisms,' not of Shakespeare with other writers, but with Shakespeare himself, quotes as similar to the present wish of Imogen, that of Volumnia in reference to Coriolanus: 'I would my son were in Arabia, and thy tribe before him,' etc.—Cor., IV, ii, 24; 'or be alive again, And dare me to the desert with thy sword.'—Mach., III, iv, 104; 'I dare meet Surrey in a wilderness, And spit upon him while I say he lies.'—Rich. II: IV, i, 74."
      ]
    },
