        "sterue] SINGER: This has been inconsiderately changed to starve in all modern editions. [See Text. Notes.]—DYCE: I do not agree with Mr Singer. They are one and the same word, whether it be used (as in the present passage) simply in the sense of perish, or in that of dying with hunger. The Folio in Cor., IV, i, has ‘Angers my Meate: I suppe upon myselfe, And so shall sterue with"
      ]
