    "13": {
      "play": "Which are the movers of a languishing death,",
      "notes": [
        "languishing] For the sake of scansion WALKER (Vers., p. 66), and ABBOTT (§ 467) after him, would pronounce this word as a disyllable, lang’ishing. Can any lover of Shakespeare’s musical language hear this without ang’sh?—Ed. 14, 15. But . . . Doctor] VAUGHAN (p. 358) presents us with the following alternative ‘articulation and scansion’ of this line: ‘But though slow, deɑd daly. I won der, doctor’; or this: ‘But though slow deɑd ly I oᴜn der, doctor.’ If, hereafter, from these pages all references to Vaughan’s ‘articulation and scansion,’ be omitted, I think it will be pardoned; but if not, I will bare my back for punishment without flinching.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "But though slow, deadly.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "QUEEN: I wonder, doctor,",
      "notes": [
        "I wonder] It is hardly conceivable that STEEVENS should have been ignorant that four editions before his own, beginning with THEOBALD, had printed ‘I do wonder’; and yet he deliberately said, ‘I have supplied the verb do for the sake of the measure.’—WALKER (Vers., p. 24) also suggested do; but for him there is some excuse; his library is known to have been scanty.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "Thou ask’st me such a question. Have I not been",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "Thy pupil long? Hast thou not learned me how",
      "notes": [
        "learn’d me] Examples of ‘learn’ thus used, in the sense of teach, are given in N. E. D. (s. v., II. 4. c.) in every century from 1200 to Shakespeare’s time. This venerable usage is still happily preserved in this country.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "18": {
