      "notes": [
        "what shew of death it makes] VAUGHAN (p. 362): Shakespeare intends ‘it’ to refer to the act of ‘dulling and stupefying the sense,’ and not any object mentioned [This last clause, I think, is not quite clear.—DELIUS says that ‘it,’ by an inexact construction, refers to ‘those she has.’ This reference Vaughan pronounces ‘if natural, still wrong.’ I cannot so see it; ‘show of death’ is only a paraphrase of ‘stupefying and dulling the sense,’ and is the object of ‘makes.’ To me, the interpretation of Delius is just.—ED.]"
