    "62": {
      "play": "Thus raps you? Are you well?",
      "notes": [
        "Thus rap’s you] WHITE (ed. i, reading wraps): That is, wraps you in contemplation, of course. The Folio, ‘raps you,’ which ridiculous reading has been hitherto preserved. [And continues to be preserved in White’s ed. ii. According to Bartlett’s Concordance this is the only instance of its use in the present tense in Shakespeare; as a past participle, ‘rapt,’ he uses it several times. I can find no reference to its present use in the N. E. D. Possibly when the letter W. is reached it may appear as a variant of wraps.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
