    "2": {
      "play": "FIRST LORD: Your Lordship is the most patient man in",
      "notes": [
        "Enter Cloten] ECCLES: The time is early the following morning.—According to DANIEL (p. 242) Day 4 begins when Iachimo issues from the trunk; and his scheme agrees with Eccles’s as to early morning."
      ]
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "loss, the most coldest that ever turned up ace.",
      "notes": [
        "turn’d vp Ace] Assuming that a game of cards is here intended, INGLEBY (Revised ed.) observes that the ‘ace is evidently here,—contrary to expectation,—a losing card; but if we can apply “turned up” to the cutting of the pack, the ace would naturally be, as it always has been, the lowest card; and, as Dr Nicholson observes, the game of cutting for stakes (if it can be dignified with the title of “game”) would best suit Cloten’s impatience and limited comprehension.’ But MURRAY (N. E. D., s. v.) assumes, and rightly, that dice are referred to, and gives as his first definition of ‘ace’ (with this present line as an example), ‘one at dice, or the side of the die marked with one pip or point.’ This, as we all know, is the lowest throw.—SCHMIDT (Lex.) says that ‘ace’ is here used with a quibble; this means, of course, that it was pronounced much like ass. And that this interpretation is not astray we learn from the only other passage where Shakespeare uses it. In Mid. N. D., after Pyramus has exclaimed ‘dye, dye, dye,’ there"
      ]
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: It would make any man cold to lose.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "FIRST LORD: But not every man patient after the noble",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "temper of your Lordship. You are most hot and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
