    "89": {
      "play": "Had that was well worth watching—it was hanged",
      "notes": [
        "well worth watching] STEEVENS: That is, that which was well lying awake for. [STAUNTON takes ‘watching’ as the term in falconry for taming the haggards by keeping them awake. That Shakespeare does use this term of falconry we all know (Desdemona says of Othello, ‘I’ll watch him tame’), but I think it doubtful that it is so used here. Is it not sufficient to take it as a mere equivalent of ‘not sleeping.’ Furthermore, is there not an absorption of the in the th of ‘worth’: ‘Had that was well worth ’ [the] watching’?—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "With tapestry of silk and silver, the story",
      "notes": []
    },
    "91": {
      "play": "Proud Cleopatra when she met her Roman",
      "notes": []
