    "18": {
      "play": "Like a full-acorned boar, a German one,",
      "notes": [
        "a Iarman on] DYCE (Strict., p. 16): Since The Sec. Part of Henry IV: II, i, the Quarto of 1600 has ‘the Iarman [i. e., German] hunting in water-worke,’ etc., I am perfectly convinced that ‘a Iarman on’ is (as Rowe saw) the old spelling for ‘a German, one.’—DOWDEN: I am not at all sure that ‘Iarman’ does not here mean german, germane. ‘Iarman’ is an obsolete form of german (occurring, for example, in Hamlet, Qq), and several early examples of german, meaning genuine, true, thorough, are cited in the N. E. D.; ‘a german one’ may thus mean a genuine one."
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "Cried “O!” and mounted; found no opposition",
      "notes": []
