    "74": {
      "play": "And left me bare to weather.",
      "notes": [
        "weather] For other instances where this means storms, tempests, see SCHMIDT (Lex.). 73, 74. false Oathes . . . perfect Honor] VAUGHAN (p. 437): Shakespeare here probably alludes to the privilege of nobility, which pledges its ‘honour,’ where ‘lower ranks take their oaths,’ or pledge their ‘honesty’; and ‘perfect honour’ means ‘honour not violated by falsehood,’ as ‘false oaths’ means oaths so violated."
      ]
