    "109": {
      "play": "That now thou tirest on, how thy memory",
      "notes": [
        "thou tyrest on] WHITNEY (Cent. Dict.): The Primary intransitive meaning of to ‘tyre’ is: To engage in pulling or tearing or rending: used especially in falconry of hawks pouncing upon their prey. The secondary meaning is: To be earnestly engaged; to dote; gloat [as in the present line].",
        "pang’d] For many other examples of verbs formed from nouns, see ABBOTT, §200; where ‘panging’ is quoted from Hen. VIII: II, iii, 15: ‘’Tis a sufferance panging As soul and body’s severing.’"
      ]
    },
