    "126": {
      "play": "To be unbent when thou hast ta’en thy stand,",
      "notes": [
        "To be vn-bent] Johnson: To have thy bow unbent, alluding to an hunter. [Did Dr Johnson drop some of his haitsches? or was the dropping in his day allowable in ‘hunter,’ as it still is in honour, hour, etc.?—Ed.]—Madden (p. 236): It was a question to be asked, for when the deer are driven by the stand, then comes the moment for action. A stand was a hiding place constructed in the thickest brake, commanding the land across which the deer were expected to pass."
      ]
