    "91": {
      "play": "QUEEN, aside  All the better. May",
      "notes": []
    },
    "92": {
      "play": "This night forestall him of the coming day!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "Queen exits, with Attendants.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: I love and hate her, for she’s fair and royal,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "And that she hath all courtly parts more exquisite",
      "notes": []
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "Than lady, ladies, woman. From every one",
      "notes": [
        "Then Lady, Ladies, Woman, from every one, etc.] WARBURTON: This line is intolerable nonsense. It should be read and printed thus, ‘Than lady Ladies; winning from each one,’ The sense of the whole is this, I love her because she has, in a more exquisite degree, all those courtly parts that ennoble (lady) women of qualities (ladies), winning from each of them the best of their good qualities, etc. ‘Lady’ is a plural verb, and ‘Ladies’ is a noun governed of it; a quaint expression in Shakespeare’s way, and suiting the folly of the character. [‘Warburton’s acuteness seems usually to have forsaken him the moment he lost his malignity. As some beasts muddy the water by trampling before they drink, so nothing is palatable to Warburton but what he has made turbid.’ Landor, Conversation between Dr. Johnson and Horne Tooke.—Ed.]—SEWARD (Note on Spanish Curate, I, i, p. 185): I cannot see any impenetrable nonsense in this, unless o’er-weaning critics will labor to expound it into such. The Poet’s text is a just climax; scil. ‘She hath all courtly parts more exquisite than any single Lady whoever; ay, than many Ladies; nay, than the whole sex put together.’ Ferdinand, speaking of his Mistress Miranda, says almost the same thing in The Tempest. ‘But you, O you, So perfect and so peerless are created Of ev’ry creature’s best.’—III, i, 47. [It is not impossible, nay, it is highly probable, that in the notes to this play we have the very last editorial work of poor, neglected, poverty-stricken Theobald. On the title-page to this, the second volume of Seward’s edition of Beaumont & Fletcher, it is stated that ‘The Custom of the Country, The Elder Brother, The Spanish Curate to page 233 are Printed under the Inspection of the late Mr Theobald.’ Theobald died in 1744. The ten volumes were long in going through the press, and are all dated 1750.—JOHNSON adopted the same interpretation as above of the present line, and MALONE adopted the reference to The Tempest.—TOLLET added an apposite reference to All’s Well: ‘Lafeu. Are you companion to the Count Rousillon? Parolles. To any count, to all counts, to what is man.’—II, iii, 202. All commentators agree in the interpretation of the present passage as first given by Theobald (probably) in Seward’s volume, except CRAIG, who has the following note on it: There are many certainly corrupt passages in this ill-printed play (we have unfortunately no Quarto to assist us);"
      ]
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "The best she hath, and she, of all compounded,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "Outsells them all. I love her therefore, but",
      "notes": []
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "Disdaining me and throwing favors on",
      "notes": []
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "The low Posthumus slanders so her judgment",
      "notes": []
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "That what’s else rare is choked. And in that point",
      "notes": []
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "I will conclude to hate her, nay, indeed,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "To be revenged upon her. For, when fools",
      "notes": [
        "when Fooles shall] THISSELTON: Cloten possibly had in view some paraphrase of the proverb ‘Fools’ haste is no speed.’ This seems to me to be confirmed by ‘are you packing sirrah’; but, at least, Pisanio practically finishes the sentence for Cloten in this sense, when he says at the end of this scene ‘This Fooles spede Be crost with slownesse; Labour be his meede.’"
      ]
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "Shall—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "[Enter Pisanio.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "Who is here? What, are you packing, sirrah?",
      "notes": [
        "packing] STAUNTON: Plotting, contriving, scheming."
      ]
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "Come hither. Ah, you precious pander! Villain,",
      "notes": [
        "Pandar, Villaine,] WALKER (Crit., i, 31): Perhaps, ‘pandar-villain!’ The reading in the edition of 1821 [Capell’s] seems more probable."
      ]
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "Where is thy lady? In a word, or else",
      "notes": []
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "Thou art straightway with the fiends.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "He draws his sword.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "PISANIO: O, good my lord—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: Where is thy lady? Or, by Jupiter—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "I will not ask again. Close villain,",
      "notes": [
        "Close] That is, secret, as in ‘still close as sure.’—I, vii, 166."
      ]
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "I’ll have this secret from thy heart or rip",
      "notes": []
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "Thy heart to find it. Is she with Posthumus,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "From whose so many weights of baseness cannot",
      "notes": []
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "A dram of worth be drawn?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "PISANIO: Alas, my lord,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "How can she be with him? When was she missed?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "He is in Rome.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: Where is she, sir? Come nearer.",
      "notes": [
        "Come nearer] HUDSON: He means ‘Come nearer to the point.’ Speak more to the purpose. [In support of this just interpretation, CRAIG quotes: ‘What need’st thou run so many miles about, When thou may’st tell thy tale a nearer way.’—Rich. III: IV, iv, 461. There is a sinister idea in Hen. V: ‘give us leave Freely to render what we have in charge; Or shall we sparingly show you far off The Dauphin’s meaning,’ etc.—I, ii, 238.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "No farther halting. Satisfy me home",
      "notes": []
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "What is become of her.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "PISANIO: O, my all-worthy lord!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: All-worthy villain!",
      "notes": [
        "Villaine] WALKER (Crit., ii, 44) devotes a chapter on Villaine and Villainie confounded, wherein the present word is the first example. ‘For “villaine” read villainie, metri gratia. This correction also spares us the repetition of “villain” three times within a few lines. The mode of address (abstractum pro concreto) is frequent in Shakespeare and his contemporary poets. Gifford, if I understand him aright, has made the same remark, Massinger, vol. iii, p. 580, ed. ii.’—[VAUGHAN makes the strange remark that ‘S. Walker suggests “villany” conjecturally, but does not adduce any examples which confirm his supposition.’ Of course, where conjectures are concerned, downright confirmation is always an open question. But Walker, in fact, presents ten or twelve examples which he himself believes amply confirm his conjecture,—a conclusion which, I think, many students will share who read his chapter.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "Discover where thy mistress is at once,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "At the next word. No more of “worthy lord”!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "Speak, or thy silence on the instant is",
      "notes": []
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "Thy condemnation and thy death.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "PISANIO: Then, sir,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "This paper is the history of my knowledge",
      "notes": [
        "This Paper] Pisanio afterwards (V, v, 330) says that this was a counterfeit letter of Posthumus which he had by accident in his pocket! It is to be feared that this is one of the instances of the ‘folly of the fiction’ which Dr Johnson found in this play; any comment on it would be, therefore, wasted on ‘unresisting imbecility.’—ED."
      ]
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "Touching her flight. He gives Cloten a paper.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: Let’s see ’t. I will pursue her",
      "notes": []
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "Even to Augustus’ throne.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "PISANIO, aside  Or this or perish.",
      "notes": [
        "Or this, or perish] JOHNSON: These words, I think, belong to Cloten. Then Pisanio, giving the paper, says to himself: ‘She’s far enough,’ etc.—RANN: Give me the paper, or thou diest.—MALONE: Cloten knew not, till it was tendered, that Pisanio had such a letter as he now presents; there could, therefore, be no question concerning his giving it freely or withholding it. These words, in my opinion, relate to Pisanio’s present conduct, and they mean, I think, ‘I must either practise this deceit upon Cloten, or perish by his fury.’—INGLEBY, by an evident oversight, adopted Johnson’s conjecture in his text with the following note: ‘The alteration, however, is not necessary to explain Pisanio’s subsequent account of this interview; for Cloten had already threatened him with death if he did not disclose Imogen’s whereabouts.’ In the Revised Ed., by his son, the error is corrected, and the present words given to Pisanio.—THISELTON: As Pisanio says this he hands Cloten the letter, the Aside not commencing until the next line. He means Cloten to understand that he yields to the latter’s threats, while he really expresses a wish that Cloten may not reach Imogen before he arrives at Augustus’s throne (which, considering the state of war, was a perilous thing to attempt, and would scarcely assist his design), or that he should perish in the attempt.—DOWDEN: Perhaps these words are not spoken aside, and are meant to deceive Cloten by apparent reluctance in showing a letter which Pisanio believes can really do no harm to Imogen."
      ]
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "She’s far enough, and what he learns by this",
      "notes": []
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "May prove his travail, not her danger.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: Humh!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "PISANIO, aside",
      "notes": []
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "I’ll write to my lord she’s dead. O Imogen,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "141": {
      "play": "Safe mayst thou wander, safe return again!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "142": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: Sirrah, is this letter true?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "143": {
      "play": "PISANIO: Sir, as I think.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "144": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: It is Posthumus’ hand, I know ’t. Sirrah, if",
      "notes": [
        "Clot. It is Posthumus hand, etc.] FLEAY (Life, etc., p. 246) believes that this play was written at different times, the last three Acts in 1606 just after Lear and Macbeth. ‘Especially should III, v, be examined,’ he says, ‘from this point of view, in which the prose part is a subsequent insertion, having some slight discrepancies with the older parts of the scene.’"
      ]
    },
    "145": {
      "play": "thou wouldst not be a villain, but do me true service,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "146": {
      "play": "undergo those employments wherein I should",
      "notes": []
    },
    "147": {
      "play": "have cause to use thee with a serious industry—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "148": {
      "play": "that is, what villainy soe’er I bid thee do to perform",
      "notes": []
    },
    "149": {
      "play": "it directly and truly—I would think thee an honest",
      "notes": []
    },
    "150": {
      "play": "man. Thou shouldst neither want my means for thy",
      "notes": []
    },
    "151": {
      "play": "relief nor my voice for thy preferment.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "152": {
      "play": "PISANIO: Well, my good lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "153": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: Wilt thou serve me? For since patiently and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "154": {
      "play": "constantly thou hast stuck to the bare fortune of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "155": {
      "play": "that beggar Posthumus, thou canst not in the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "156": {
      "play": "course of gratitude but be a diligent follower of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "mine. Wilt thou serve me?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "PISANIO: Sir, I will.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "159": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: Give me thy hand. Here’s my purse. Gives",
      "notes": []
    },
    "160": {
      "play": "him money. Hast any of thy late master’s garments",
      "notes": []
    },
    "161": {
      "play": "in thy possession?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "162": {
      "play": "PISANIO: I have, my lord, at my lodging the same suit he",
      "notes": []
    },
    "163": {
      "play": "wore when he took leave of my lady and mistress.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "164": {
      "play": "CLOTEN: The first service thou dost me, fetch that suit",
      "notes": []
    },
    "165": {
      "play": "hither. Let it be thy first service. Go.",
      "notes": []
    },
