    "74": {
      "play": "This youth, howe’er distressed, appears he hath had",
      "notes": [
        "how ere distrest, appeares he hath] KNIGHT (reading ‘howe’er distrest’d he appears, hath’): [The comma, inserted by Capell after ‘appears,’] is to us unintelligible; we have, therefore, ventured on the transposition in our text, assuming that the printer, having left out the ‘he’ in his first proof, inserted it as a correction in the wrong place—one of the commonest of typographical errors.",
        "appeares] ABBOTT (§ 295) surmises that ‘perhaps “appear” was sometimes used as an active verb.’ (See III, iv, 165, where Abbott thinks that it may be used reflexively.) But afterwards (§ 411) he inclines to think that the better way is to consider the phrase as a confusion of two constructions: ‘He hath had, (it) appears, good ancestors,’ and ‘He appears to have had.’"
      ]
    },
    "75": {
      "play": "Good ancestors.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "76": {
      "play": "ARVIRAGUS, as Cadwal  How angel-like he sings!",
