      "notes": [
        "the Gates of Luds-Towne] See III, i, 39."
      ]
    },
    "155": {
      "play": "Yield, rustic mountaineer!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "156": {
      "play": "[They fight and exit.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "[Enter Belarius as Morgan and Arviragus as]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "Cadwal.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "159": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  No company’s abroad?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "160": {
      "play": "ARVIRAGUS, as Cadwal",
      "notes": []
    },
    "161": {
      "play": "None in the world. You did mistake him sure.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "162": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan",
      "notes": []
    },
    "163": {
      "play": "I cannot tell. Long is it since I saw him,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "164": {
      "play": "But time hath nothing blurred those lines of favor",
      "notes": [
        "lines of Favour] This is nearly equivalent to Cloten’s own expression in the preceding scene where he speaks of ‘the Lines of my body.’ ‘Favour’ may, possibly, refer more especially to the features.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "165": {
      "play": "Which then he wore. The snatches in his voice",
      "notes": [
        "the snatches in his voice] DOWDEN: Catches, seizures, meaning, I think, a violent check in speech, which is followed by a ‘burst of speaking.’ I know of no other example; but the Scottish and Irish word ‘ganch,’ verb and substantive, means as verb to stammer, and as substantive a snatch at anything, which illustrates the double meaning. [Fluellen, in describing Bardolph to King Henry, says ‘his lips blows at his nose.’—Hen. V: III, vi, 113.—ED.]",
        "burst of speaking] JOHNSON: This is one of our Author’s strokes of observation. An abrupt and tumultuous utterance very frequently accompanies a confused and cloudy understanding."
      ]
    },
    "166": {
      "play": "And burst of speaking were as his. I am absolute",
      "notes": []
    },
    "167": {
      "play": "’Twas very Cloten.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "168": {
      "play": "ARVIRAGUS, as Cadwal  In this place we left them.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "169": {
      "play": "I wish my brother make good time with him,",
      "notes": [
        "make good time with him] ECCLES: That is, make good use or advantage of the time."
      ]
    },
    "170": {
      "play": "You say he is so fell.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "171": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  Being scarce made up,",
      "notes": [
        "Being scarse made vp] INGLEBY: That is, imperfectly developed; as we say—‘not all there.’ Cf Rich. III: I, i, 21, ‘scarce half made up.’ Cloten was then but a youth, though now a middle-aged man.—VAUGHAN (p. 480): Theo-"
      ]
    },
    "172": {
      "play": "I mean to man, he had not apprehension",
      "notes": []
    },
    "173": {
      "play": "Of roaring terrors; for defect of judgment",
      "notes": []
    },
    "174": {
      "play": "Is oft the cause of fear.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "175": {
      "play": "[Enter Guiderius as Polydor, carrying Cloten’s head.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "176": {
      "play": "But see, thy brother.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "177": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS, as Polydor",
      "notes": []
    },
    "178": {
      "play": "This Cloten was a fool, an empty purse;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "179": {
      "play": "There was no money in ’t. Not Hercules",
      "notes": []
    },
    "180": {
      "play": "Could have knocked out his brains, for he had none.",
      "notes": [
        "Braines, for he had none] STEEVENS: Compare, ‘Hector shall have a great catch, if he knock out either of your brains, a’ were as good crack a fusty nut with no kernel.’—Tro. & Cress., II, i, iii."
      ]
    },
    "181": {
      "play": "Yet I not doing this, the fool had borne",
      "notes": []
    },
    "182": {
      "play": "My head as I do his.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "183": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  What hast thou done?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "184": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS, as Polydor",
      "notes": []
    },
    "185": {
      "play": "I am perfect what: cut off one Cloten’s head,",
      "notes": [
        "I am perfect what] JOHNSON: I am well-informed, what. So, in this play, ‘I am perfect, that the Pannonians . . . are now in Armes.’—III, i, 80. [This can hardly be called one of Dr. Johnson’s happiest definitions. The word, however, needs none.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "186": {
      "play": "Son to the Queen, after his own report,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "187": {
      "play": "Who called me traitor mountaineer, and swore",
      "notes": []
    },
    "188": {
      "play": "With his own single hand he’d take us in,",
      "notes": [
        "heel’d take vs in] JOHNSON: To ‘take in’ was the phrase in use for to apprehend an outlaw, or to make him amenable to public justice.—STEEVENS: To ‘take in’ means, simply, to conquer, to subdue. So in Ant. & Cleop., ‘quickly cut the Ionian sea, And take in Toryne.’—III, vii, 24.—MALONE: Cloten had not threatened to render these outlaws ‘amenable to justice,’ but to kill them with his own hand. See line 133, above. In line 185 ‘fetch us in’ is used in the sense assigned by Dr Johnson to the present phrase."
      ]
    },
    "189": {
      "play": "Displace our heads where, thank the gods, they",
      "notes": []
    },
    "190": {
      "play": "grow,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "191": {
      "play": "And set them on Lud’s Town.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "192": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  We are all undone.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "193": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS, as Polydor",
      "notes": []
    },
    "194": {
      "play": "Why, worthy father, what have we to lose",
      "notes": []
    },
    "195": {
      "play": "But that he swore to take, our lives? The law",
      "notes": []
    },
    "196": {
      "play": "Protects not us. Then why should we be tender",
      "notes": []
    },
    "197": {
      "play": "To let an arrogant piece of flesh threat us,",
      "notes": [
        "an arrogant peece of flesh] Feste says, ‘thou wert as pretty a piece of Eve’s flesh as any in Illyria.’—Twelfth Night, I, v, 30.—DOWDEN quotes Dogberry, who says that he himself is ‘as pretty a piece of flesh as any in Messina.’—Much Ado, IV, ii, 85."
      ]
    },
    "198": {
      "play": "Play judge and executioner all himself,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "199": {
      "play": "For we do fear the law? What company",
      "notes": [
        "For] Other examples of ‘for’ used as here, in the sense of because, may be found in ABBOTT, § 151; but this special sense is not needed by those editors who adopt the text of F2, which HUNTER (ii, 297) says is ‘clearly the true reading.’ A majority of the best editors do not, however, agree with him.—DELIGHTON thus interprets the text before us: ‘We do not enjoy the protection of the law; then why should we be of such tender conscience as to let an arrogant lump of clay like this threaten us, act the part of judge and executioner all in one, simply because of our respect for law?’ i. e., we do not enjoy the benefits of the law, why should we submit to insults, etc., which those who do enjoy them are bound to submit to; why not take the law into our own hands, seeing it will not help us to redress?—[In the Text. Notes Capell’s text is correctly set down as following ROWE. In his Errata, however, he withdraws it, and anticipates the Var. ’78.—ED.] 176, 177. his Honor Was nothing but mutation] THEOBALD: What has his ‘Honor’ to do here, in his being changeable in this sort? in his acting as a madman or not? I have ventured to substitute humour; and the meaning seems plainly this: ‘Tho’ he was always fickle to the last degree, and governed by Humour, not sound sense; yet not madness itself could make him so hardy as to attempt an"
      ]
    },
    "200": {
      "play": "Discover you abroad?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "201": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  No single soul",
      "notes": []
    },
    "202": {
      "play": "Can we set eye on, but in all safe reason",
      "notes": []
    },
    "203": {
      "play": "He must have some attendants. Though his humor",
      "notes": []
    },
    "204": {
      "play": "Was nothing but mutation—ay, and that",
      "notes": []
    },
    "205": {
      "play": "From one bad thing to worse—not frenzy,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "206": {
      "play": "Not absolute madness could so far have raved",
      "notes": []
    },
    "207": {
      "play": "To bring him here alone. Although perhaps",
      "notes": []
    },
    "208": {
      "play": "It may be heard at court that such as we",
      "notes": []
    },
    "209": {
      "play": "Cave here, hunt here, are outlaws, and in time",
      "notes": []
    },
    "210": {
      "play": "May make some stronger head, the which he",
      "notes": []
    },
    "211": {
      "play": "hearing—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "212": {
      "play": "As it is like him—might break out and swear",
      "notes": []
    },
    "213": {
      "play": "He’d fetch us in, yet is ’t not probable",
      "notes": [
        "Heel’d fetch vs in] See line 162, ‘heel’d take vs in.’"
      ]
    },
    "214": {
      "play": "To come alone, either he so undertaking",
      "notes": [
        "either] ‘Perhaps, in some measure,’ says WALKER (Vers., 103), ‘all words in -ther are frequently used as monosyllables, or so nearly such that in a metrical point of view they may be regarded as monosyllables. Some, as whether, were undoubtedly contracted, whe’r. This usage is more frequent in some words than in others, e. g., in whether than in hither, whither, etc. Either occurs not unfrequently even in the unaccented places.’"
      ]
    },
    "215": {
      "play": "Or they so suffering. Then on good ground we fear,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "216": {
      "play": "If we do fear this body hath a tail",
      "notes": []
    },
    "217": {
      "play": "More perilous than the head.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "218": {
      "play": "ARVIRAGUS, as Cadwal  Let ord’nance",
      "notes": [
        "Ord’nance] MURRAY (N. E. D.): That which is ordained or decreed by the Deity or Fate. [Present passage here quoted.]"
      ]
    },
    "219": {
      "play": "Come as the gods foresay it. Howsoe’er,",
      "notes": [
        "fore-say] MURRAY (N. E. D.) defines this word by ‘to say beforehand,’ ‘foretell,’ ‘predict.’—DOWDEN suggests, and I agree with him, that it here means ‘to determine,’ ‘will,’ rather than ‘predict.’ 193–194. I had no minde To hunt this day] ECCLES: Belarius seems to regret his having been induced to depart from home, as if the misfortune he laments had been the consequence of his absence from thence, when it is evident, from their first appearance in this scene, together with Imogen, when they were only preparing to set out, they have never departed from the cave, except during the short period while he and Arviragus go out to search for the companions of Cloten; and the latter goes off fighting with Guiderius and Cloten is killed. This appears to have been a very unaccountable oversight in the writer. [Where is the ‘oversight’? It is a dramatic necessity that they should be as near as may be to the cave.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "220": {
      "play": "My brother hath done well.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "221": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  I had no mind",
      "notes": []
    },
    "222": {
      "play": "To hunt this day. The boy Fidele’s sickness",
      "notes": []
    },
    "223": {
      "play": "Did make my way long forth.",
      "notes": [
        "Did make my way long forth] JOHNSON: Fidele’s sickness made my walk forth from the cave tedious."
      ]
    },
    "224": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS, as Polydor  With his own sword,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "225": {
      "play": "Which he did wave against my throat, I have ta’en",
      "notes": []
    },
    "226": {
      "play": "His head from him. I’ll throw ’t into the creek",
      "notes": [
        "throw’t into the Creeke] DOWDEN’S comment on ‘Creeke,’ that it ‘probably means a “stream,” see line 238,’ sounds strange enough to us Americans, to whom ‘creek,’ as the designation of a small stream, is familiar enough. What are ‘rivers’ in England, such as the Thames, would be probably here called ‘creeks.’ ‘Gunpowder Creek,’ which every traveller in the cars from the North to Washington crosses, is five thousand one hundred feet wide,—that is, almost exactly a mile.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "227": {
      "play": "Behind our rock, and let it to the sea",
      "notes": []
    },
    "228": {
      "play": "And tell the fishes he’s the Queen’s son, Cloten.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "229": {
      "play": "[That’s all I reck.   He exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "230": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  I fear ’twill be revenged.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "231": {
      "play": "Would, Polydor, thou hadst not done ’t, though valor",
      "notes": []
    },
    "232": {
      "play": "Becomes thee well enough.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "233": {
      "play": "ARVIRAGUS, as Cadwal  Would I had done ’t,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "234": {
      "play": "So the revenge alone pursued me. Polydor,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "235": {
      "play": "I love thee brotherly, but envy much",
      "notes": []
    },
    "236": {
      "play": "Thou hast robbed me of this deed. I would revenges",
      "notes": []
    },
    "237": {
      "play": "That possible strength might meet would seek us",
      "notes": []
