    "306": {
      "play": "Not as Death’s dart being laughed at; his right cheek",
      "notes": [
        "Not as deaths dart being laugh’d at] CAPELL (p. 116): ‘Being laugh’d at’ means ‘for I saw it laugh’d at,’ and is a reason why he could not think it was the ‘dart’ that had struck him.—ECCLES: I would amend by reading ‘been laugh’d at,’ that is, ‘As if some fly had only tickled slumber, not as if death’s dart had been laughed at.’—VAUGIHAN (p. 490) proposes the same emendation, with the explanation that ‘had’ is to be carried on from ‘tickled’ to ‘being laugh’d at.’"
      ]
    },
