        "The Dreame’s heere still: euen when I wake it is] STAUNTON (Athenaeum, 14 June, 1873): Another of the countless instances where Shakespeare’s meaning has been enfeebled or destroyed by an erroneous punctuation point: ‘The dream’s here still, even when I wake! It is,’ etc. [I cannot see any improvement. On the contrary, it seems to me to enfeeble the force of ‘here.’—ED.]"
