    "445": {
      "play": "The brawns of Hercules; but his Jovial face—",
      "notes": [
        "Iouiall] STEEVENS: This signifies here such a face as belongs to Jove. It is frequently used in the same sense by other old dramatic writers. Thus, in Heywood’s Rape of Lucrece: ‘Brutus. Thou Ioviall hand held up thy Scepter high, And let not,’ etc., 1630, [sig. k, verso]."
