    "472": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: But what from Rome?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "473": {
      "play": "CAPTAIN: The Senate hath stirred up the confiners",
      "notes": []
    },
    "474": {
      "play": "And gentlemen of Italy, most willing spirits",
      "notes": [
        "Confiner] MURRAY (N. E. D., s. v. 2.): That is, one living within the confines, an inhabitant. [Other than the present passage, the only quotation is—1595, Daniel, Civil Warres, i, lxviii: ‘Happie confiners you of other landes.’]—DYCE, following Capell, Steevens, and Malone, places an accent on the first syllable, ‘confíners.’ ‘Daniel accents conf-ners,’ says Murray. [I am not quite sure that the quotation from Daniel bears out the definition of ‘an inhabitant.’ Daniel represents the populace, who accompany ‘Bullinbrooke’ to the sea-shore to begin his six years of exile, as lamenting that the ocean hems them ‘within the waterie prison of its waves,’ and none escape ‘the eyes of wrath.’ ‘Happie confiners,’ they say, ‘you of other landes, That shift your soyle, and oft scape tyrants hands.’ Does not ‘confiners’ here point to ‘borderers,’ which is Murray’s first definition, rather than to mere ‘inhabitants’? To escape a tyrant cannot those who live on the confines, on the borders, pass from one country to another more swiftly and readily than those who are ‘stopt by the fearefull ocean’ or are inhabitants of inland cities?—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "475": {
      "play": "That promise noble service, and they come",
      "notes": []
    },
    "476": {
      "play": "Under the conduct of bold Iachimo,",
      "notes": [
        "Syenna’s Brother] STEEVENS: That is (as I suppose Shakespeare to have meant), brother to the Prince of Sienna; but, unluckily, Sienna was a republic. See W. Thomas’s Hist. of Italye, 1561, p. 7, b.—DOWDEN: But not in drama. In Beaumont & Fletcher’s Woman Pleased we find a Duke of Sienna."
      ]
    },
    "477": {
      "play": "Siena’s brother.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "478": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: When expect you them?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "479": {
      "play": "CAPTAIN: With the next benefit o’ th’ wind.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "480": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: This forwardness",
      "notes": []
    },
    "481": {
      "play": "Makes our hopes fair. Command our present numbers",
      "notes": []
    },
    "482": {
      "play": "Be mustered; bid the Captains look to ’t.—Now, sir,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "483": {
      "play": "What have you dreamed of late of this war’s purpose?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "484": {
      "play": "SOOTHSAYER: Last night the very gods showed me a vision—",
      "notes": [
        "the very Gods] JOHNSON: It was no common dream, but sent from the very gods, or the gods themselves.—WALKER (Crit., ii, 328): That is, not even the gods, but the gods beyond a doubt; or perhaps the gods in person, as in Virgil, Æn., iii, 172.",
        "a vision] HERFORD: This episode was probably suggested by Holinshed’s description of Aulus Plautius’s invasion under Claudius, when ‘the mariners and men of war’ were encouraged by seeing ‘a fierie leme [light] to shoot out of the east towards the west, which way their course lay.’—Stone’s Holinshed, p. 15."
      ]
    },
    "485": {
      "play": "I fast and prayed for their intelligence—thus:",
      "notes": [
        "I fast] ABBOTT (§ 342) gives a long list of verbs ending in t which do not add -ed in the participle.",
        "Intelligence] SCHMIDT (Lex.): That is, mental intercourse. 431, 432. thus: I saw Ioues Bird] VAUGHAN (p. 497): ‘Jove’s bird’ is the nominative case and should commence the sentence. We should read: ‘Thus I saw; Jove’s bird the Roman eagle,’ etc. 433, 434. South, . . . West, There vanish’d in the Sun-beames] MADDEN (p. 215, foot-note): The soothsayer notes that the Eagle ‘vanish’d in the sunbeams.’ This annoyance must have occurred constantly on a bright morning with a strong north-northwesterly wind."
      ]
    },
    "486": {
      "play": "I saw Jove’s bird, the Roman eagle, winged",
      "notes": []
    },
    "487": {
      "play": "From the spongy south to this part of the west,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "488": {
      "play": "There vanished in the sunbeams, which portends—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "489": {
      "play": "Unless my sins abuse my divination—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "490": {
      "play": "Success to th’ Roman host.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "491": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: Dream often so,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "492": {
      "play": "And never false.—Soft, ho, what trunk is here",
      "notes": []
    },
    "493": {
      "play": "Without his top? The ruin speaks that sometime",
      "notes": []
    },
    "494": {
      "play": "It was a worthy building. How, a page?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "495": {
      "play": "Or dead or sleeping on him? But dead rather,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "496": {
      "play": "For nature doth abhor to make his bed",
      "notes": [
        "bed] See Text. Notes for what appears to be eighteenth century squeamishness.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "497": {
      "play": "With the defunct or sleep upon the dead.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "498": {
      "play": "Let’s see the boy’s face.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "499": {
      "play": "CAPTAIN: He’s alive, my lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "500": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: He’ll then instruct us of this body.—Young one,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "501": {
      "play": "Inform us of thy fortunes, for it seems",
      "notes": []
    },
    "502": {
      "play": "They crave to be demanded. Who is this",
      "notes": []
    },
    "503": {
      "play": "Thou mak’st thy bloody pillow? Or who was he",
      "notes": []
    },
    "504": {
      "play": "That, otherwise than noble nature did,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "505": {
      "play": "Hath altered that good picture? What’s thy interest",
      "notes": []
    },
    "506": {
      "play": "In this sad wrack? How came ’t? Who is ’t?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "507": {
      "play": "What art thou?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "508": {
      "play": "IMOGEN, as Fidele  I am nothing; or if not,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "509": {
      "play": "Nothing to be were better. This was my master,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "510": {
      "play": "A very valiant Briton, and a good,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "511": {
      "play": "That here by mountaineers lies slain. Alas,",
      "notes": [
        "There is] For other examples of the ‘inflection in -s preceding a plural subject,’ see ABBOTT, § 335."
      ]
    },
    "512": {
      "play": "There is no more such masters. I may wander",
      "notes": []
    },
    "513": {
      "play": "From east to occident, cry out for service,",
      "notes": [
        "cry out for Seruice] WALKER (Crit., iii, 327): Does this mean make public proclamation of my wish to enter into service? as outcry for auction."
      ]
    },
    "514": {
      "play": "Try many, all good, serve truly, never",
      "notes": [
        "Try many, all good: serue truly: neuer] STEEVENS: We may be certain that this line was originally complete. I would, therefore, for the sake of metre, read: ‘—and all good,’ etc. [This ‘and’ already stood in the texts of Johnson and Capell! Steevens must have known it.—Ed.]—WYATT: The commas punctuate Imogen’s sobs. [After this palmariam note by Wyatt, anyone who could meddle with the scansion of this line or attempt, after counting off the syllables on his fingers, to amend it, would have held the pail while Malone whitewashed Shakespeare’s bust.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "515": {
      "play": "Find such another master.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "516": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: ’Lack, good youth,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "517": {
      "play": "Thou mov’st no less with thy complaining than",
      "notes": []
    },
    "518": {
      "play": "Thy master in bleeding. Say his name, good friend.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "519": {
      "play": "IMOGEN, as Fidele",
      "notes": []
    },
    "520": {
      "play": "Richard du Champ. Aside. If I do lie and do",
      "notes": []
    },
    "521": {
      "play": "No harm by it, though the gods hear, I hope",
      "notes": []
    },
    "522": {
      "play": "They’ll pardon it.—Say you, sir?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "523": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: Thy name?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "524": {
      "play": "IMOGEN, as Fidele  Fidele, sir.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "525": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: Thou dost approve thyself the very same;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "526": {
      "play": "Thy name well fits thy faith, thy faith thy name.",
      "notes": [
        "Thy Name well fits thy Faith] Thus, in Henry V, where Pistol, as he"
      ]
    },
    "527": {
      "play": "Wilt take thy chance with me? I will not say",
      "notes": []
    },
    "528": {
      "play": "Thou shalt be so well mastered, but be sure",
      "notes": []
    },
    "529": {
      "play": "No less beloved. The Roman Emperor’s letters",
      "notes": []
    },
    "530": {
      "play": "Sent by a consul to me should not sooner",
      "notes": []
    },
    "531": {
      "play": "Than thine own worth prefer thee. Go with me.",
      "notes": [
        "prefere thee] That is, recommend, advance. See II, iii, 49, and line 490, below."
      ]
    },
    "532": {
      "play": "IMOGEN, as Fidele",
      "notes": []
    },
    "533": {
      "play": "I’ll follow, sir. But first, an ’t please the gods,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "534": {
      "play": "I’ll hide my master from the flies as deep",
      "notes": []
    },
    "535": {
      "play": "As these poor pickaxes can dig; and when",
      "notes": [
        "Pickaxes] JOHNSON: Meaning her fingers."
      ]
    },
    "536": {
      "play": "With wild-wood leaves and weeds I ha’ strewed his",
      "notes": [
        "wild wood-leaues & weeds] The CAMBRIDGE EDITORS have conjectured that the true reading here is ‘wild-wood flowers.’ Every conjecture from this source is worthy of all respect. At first blush this one seems unquestionable. To test it, Imogen’s probable purpose in selecting ‘wood-leaves’ must be analysed. That these leaves are coupled with ‘weeds’ gives us a clue. Flowers are tokens of grief and sorrow. Yet these are not the emotions that predominate here,—but rather one overwhelming horror, where flowers would be inappropriate. Leaves, not petals, must be strewed on the bloody abhorrent corpse—and they must be stiff, harsh leaves from forest trees to match the weeds, the nettles, and darnels, whereon are no gay blooms. Can ‘wild-wood leaves’ suit this mood? It is conceivable that leaves from the ‘wild-wood’ might be those of gay wild-flowers, pale primroses or violets, or azured harebells. Hence, I venture modestly to think that the Folio is right.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "537": {
      "play": "grave",
      "notes": []
    },
    "538": {
      "play": "And on it said a century of prayers,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "539": {
      "play": "Such as I can, twice o’er, I’ll weep and sigh,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "540": {
      "play": "And leaving so his service, follow you,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "541": {
      "play": "So please you entertain me.",
      "notes": [
        "entertaine mee] MALONE: That is, hire me; receive me into your service."
      ]
    },
    "542": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: Ay, good youth,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "543": {
      "play": "And rather father thee than master thee.—My friends,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "544": {
      "play": "The boy hath taught us manly duties. Let us",
      "notes": []
    },
    "545": {
      "play": "Find out the prettiest daisied plot we can,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "546": {
      "play": "And make him with our pikes and partisans",
      "notes": []
    },
    "547": {
      "play": "A grave. Come, arm him.—Boy, he’s preferred",
      "notes": []
    },
    "548": {
      "play": "By thee to us, and he shall be interred",
      "notes": []
    },
    "549": {
      "play": "As soldiers can. Be cheerful; wipe thine eyes.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "550": {
      "play": "Some falls are means the happier to arise.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "551": {
      "play": "They exit, the Soldiers carrying Cloten’s body.",
      "notes": [
        "Exeunt] ANON. (Blackwood, Feb., 1833, p. 153): The scene is perfect. The flow and ebb of passion is felt by us to be obeying, like the sea, the mysterious law of nature. The huge waves of woe have subsided almost into a calm. The strength of love is now the support of Imogen’s life—and the sense of duty. She has no wish either to die or to live; but her despair is no longer distraction; and having grieved till she could grieve no more, and reached the utmost limits of sorrow, there she is willing submissively to endure her lot. ‘Leaving so his service!’ not till with her own fingers she had helped to dig her master’s grave! That done, and he buried, ‘I follow you, so please you entertain me.’ The warrior bids her ‘be cheerful and wipe her eyes’; and we can believe that Imogen obeys one-half of the injunction—that she does ‘wipe her eyes’; but as to being ‘cheerful,’ never more may a smile visit for a moment that beautiful countenance—though Lucius, looking on it, may believe that his page is happy. To him she is but Fidele; to us—Imogen. It is wonderful how our pity is never impaired by our knowledge, all the while, that the corpse is not that of Posthumus but Cloten’s. Perhaps we forget that it is so; surely there is no interruption given to our sympathy; we partake in the same delusion, which is only dispelled at last, to our great relief, by the last words of Lucius, ‘Some falls are means the happier to arise.’ It was just the same with our feelings for Imogen herself in the forest-cave. The young princes believed her dead—and we, though we knew she was but in a swoon, believed so too—almost sufficiently for any amount of sorrow. The thought that Fidele was not dead but sleeping, was so dim, that it marred not the emotions with which we beheld her funeral rites, and heard the dirge chanted, to the scattering over her fair body of leaves and flowers. Poor Cloten! He must have been a fine animal, to be mistaken, a headless trunk, for Posthumus. ———— END OF SCENE ————"
      ]
    }
  },
  "ACT 4 SCENE 3": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Cymbeline, Lords, Pisanio, and Attendants.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Again, and bring me word how ’tis with her.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "[An Attendant exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "A fever, with the absence of her son;",
      "notes": [
        "A Feavour] BUCKNILL (p. 225): The wicked queen, who bore down all with her brain, is struck with disease of the brain, when her schemes fail. She lies ‘upon a desperate bed.’ Towards the end of the play we learn the fatal result ‘with horror, madly dying,’ though, like the death of Constance and of Lady Macbeth, it is hidden from view. Shakespeare sometimes places before his audience scenes of death, whose terror can hardly be exceeded, as that of King John and Cardinal Beaufort; but the innate delicacy, which is not inconsistent with much verbal grossness, prevents him from so exhibiting a woman."
      ]
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "A madness, of which her life’s in danger. Heavens,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "How deeply you at once do touch me! Imogen,",
      "notes": [
        "touch me] That is, as frequently in Shakespeare, wound. Thus in V, iii, 14."
      ]
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "The great part of my comfort, gone; my queen",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "Upon a desperate bed, and in a time",
      "notes": []
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "When fearful wars point at me; her son gone,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "So needful for this present. It strikes me past",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "The hope of comfort.—But for thee, fellow,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "Who needs must know of her departure and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "Dost seem so ignorant, we’ll enforce it from thee",
      "notes": []
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "By a sharp torture.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "PISANIO: Sir, my life is yours.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "I humbly set it at your will. But for my mistress,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "I nothing know where she remains, why gone,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "Nor when she purposes return. Beseech your",
      "notes": []
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "Highness,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "Hold me your loyal servant.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "LORD: Good my liege,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "The day that she was missing, he was here.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "I dare be bound he’s true and shall perform",
      "notes": [
        "subiection] SCHMIDT (Lex.): Service as a subject."
      ]
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "All parts of his subjection loyally. For Cloten,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "There wants no diligence in seeking him,",
      "notes": [
        "There wants no diligence] ABBOTT (§ 297): 'Wants' is probably here not impersonal, but intransitive—'is wanting.'"
      ]
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "And will no doubt be found.",
      "notes": [
        "And will no doubt] For other examples of the 'omission of the nominative,' see ABBOTT, § 400."
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: The time is troublesome.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "To Pisanio. We’ll slip you for a season, but our jealousy",
      "notes": [
        "slip you for a season] SCHMIDT (Lex.): That is, make or let loose. Used of greyhounds allowed to start for game. 27, 28. our iealousie Do's yet depend] JOHNSON: My suspicion is yet undetermined; if I do not condemn you, I likewise have not acquitted you.",
        "iealousie] SCHMIDT (Lex., s. v. 2.): Suspicion in any way."
      ]
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "Does yet depend.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "LORD: So please your Majesty,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "The Roman legions, all from Gallia drawn,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "Are landed on your coast with a supply",
      "notes": []
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "Of Roman gentlemen by the Senate sent.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Now for the counsel of my son and queen!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "I am amazed with matter.",
      "notes": [
        "I am amaz’d with matter] STEEVENS: That is, confounded by a variety of business."
      ]
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "LORD: Good my liege,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "Your preparation can affront no less",
      "notes": [
        "Your preparation can affront] JOHNSON: Your forces are able to face such an army as we hear the enemy will bring against us."
      ]
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "Than what you hear of. Come more, for more you’re",
      "notes": []
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "ready.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "The want is but to put those powers in motion",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "That long to move.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: I thank you. Let’s withdraw,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "And meet the time as it seeks us. We fear not",
      "notes": [
        "meete the Time, as it seekes vs] CAPELL (p. 117): The intention of the speaker is—meet it with spirit, with the same spirit with which it meets us; the sentiment is weakly express’d on purpose to show his inward dejection."
      ]
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "What can from Italy annoy us, but",
      "notes": []
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "We grieve at chances here. Away.",
      "notes": [
        "We greeue at chances heere. Away] WALKER (Vers., 273): Single lines of four or five or six or seven syllables, interspersed amidst the ordinary blank verse of ten, are not to be considered as irregularities; they belong to Shakespeare’s system of metre. On the other hand, lines of eight or nine syllables, as they are at variance with the general rhythm of his poetry (at least, if my ears do not deceive me, this is the case), so they scarcely ever occur in his plays,—it were hardly too much to say, not at all. I would arrange [by making ‘Away’ a separate"
      ]
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "They exit. Pisanio remains.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "PISANIO: I heard no letter from my master since",
      "notes": [
        "I heard no Letter from my Master] MALONE: Perhaps ‘letter’ here means, not an epistle, but the elemental part of a syllable. This might have been a phrase in Shakespeare’s time. We yet say, I have not heard a syllable from him."
      ]
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "I wrote him Imogen was slain. ’Tis strange.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "Nor hear I from my mistress, who did promise",
      "notes": []
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "To yield me often tidings. Neither know I",
      "notes": []
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "What is betid to Cloten, but remain",
      "notes": []
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "Perplexed in all. The heavens still must work.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "Wherein I am false I am honest; not true, to be true.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "These present wars shall find I love my country,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "Even to the note o’ th’ King, or I’ll fall in them.",
      "notes": [
        "to the note o’th’King] JOHNSON: I will so distinguish myself the king shall remark my valour. ———— END OF SCENE ————"
      ]
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "All other doubts, by time let them be cleared.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "Fortune brings in some boats that are not steered.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "[He exits.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "ACT 4 SCENE 4": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Belarius as Morgan, Guiderius as Polydor,]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "and Arviragus as Cadwal.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS, as Polydor",
      "notes": []
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "The noise is round about us.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  Let us from it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "ARVIRAGUS, as Cadwal",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "What pleasure, sir, find we in life, to lock it",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "From action and adventure?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS, as Polydor  Nay, what hope",
      "notes": []
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "Have we in hiding us? This way the Romans",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "Must or for Britons slay us or receive us",
      "notes": []
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "For barbarous and unnatural revolts",
      "notes": [
        "Revolts] STEEVENS: That is, revolters. So in King John: ‘Lead me to the revolts in England here.’ —V, iv, 7. [See ABBOTT (§ 433) for other examples of ‘Participial Nouns.’]"
      ]
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "During their use, and slay us after.",
      "notes": [
        "During their vse] RANN: So long as they shall retain us in their service.—HUDSON: This may mean ‘as long as they have any use for us’; or, perhaps, during their present armed occupancy."
      ]
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  Sons,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "We’ll higher to the mountains, there secure us.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "To the King’s party there’s no going. Newness",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "Of Cloten’s death—we being not known, not mustered",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "Among the bands—may drive us to a render",
      "notes": [
        "a render] JOHNSON: An account of our place of abode. This dialogue is a just representation of the superfluous caution of an old man.—STEEVENS: Thus, in Timon: ‘And send for thus, to make their sorrow’d render.’—V, i, 152."
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "Where we have lived, and so extort from ’s that",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
