  "ACT 5 SCENE 2": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Lucius, Iachimo, and the Roman army at one]",
      "notes": [
        "Enter, etc.] KNIGHT holds that the minuteness of the stage directions in the first four Scenes of this Act savours of youth, and is possibly due to the fact that we here have the remnants of an early sketch which Shakespeare at a later period elaborated. [In Garrick’s Version the stage direction and opening lines are as follows: ‘A FIELD OF BATTLE. A grand Fight between the Romans and Britons: the Romans are drove off. Enter Posthumus and Iachimo fighting. Iachimo drops his Sword. Posthumus. Or yield thee, Roman, or thou dy’st. Iachimo. Peasant, behold my breast. Post. No, take thy life and mend it. [Exit Post.] Iachimo. The heaviness and sin,’ etc., etc., as in the original.—Ed.] 6, 7. and then leaues him] RUGGLES (p. 38): This mercy has a rich reward. Had Posthumus put Iachimo to death, he would have slain the only witness that could fully confirm Imogen’s truth."
      ]
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "[door, and the Briton army at another, Leonatus Posthumus]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "following like a poor soldier. They march over and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "go out. Then enter again, in skirmish, Iachimo and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "Posthumus. He vanquisheth and disarmeth Iachimo,",
      "notes": [
        "I did] CRAIG: These two 'I did's' are awkward. It is very likely, I think, that Shakespeare here wrote Aye. It must be remembered that Aye is always printed 'I' in the Folios."
      ]
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "and then leaves him.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "IACHIMO: The heaviness and guilt within my bosom",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "Takes off my manhood. I have belied a lady,",
      "notes": [
        "the Heauens fought] STEEVENS: So in Judges, v, 20: 'They fought from heaven; the stars in their courses fought against Sisera.'",
        "the King himselfe, etc.] CAPELL (p. 118): The description that begins at these words, and is concluded in the speech that comes after, is worded with such conciseness in some parts, clogged with so much parenthetical matter in others, and its images follow so thick one upon the heels of another, that a more than ordinary attention is necessary to gain due understanding of it.",
        "the King himself] tence and the three it is followed by are put absolutely; after which the construction is regular as far down as the words ‘athwart the lane’ [line 23], where we must supply throwing himself; for ‘soldiour’ is not connected with anything, but the sense is broke off at it. This turning of the tide of battle by Belarius and his two sons is derived from an incident narrated by Holinshed (Hist. of Scotland, p. 155), which is quoted in part by MALONE and MUSGRAVE. It stands thus in Holinshed: ‘The Danes being backed with the mountaine, were constreined to leaue the same, and with all speed to come forward vpon their enimies, that by ioüing they might auoid the danger of the Scottishmens arrowes and darts: by this means therfore they came to handstrokes, in maner before the signe was giuen on either part to the battell. The fight was cruell on both sides: and nothing hindered the Scots so much, as going about to cut off the heads of the Danes, euer as they might ouercome them. Which maner being noted of the Danes, and perceiuing that there was no hope of life but in victorie, they rushed foorth with such violence vpon their aduersaries, that first the right, and then after the left wing of the Scots, was constreined to retire and flee backe, the middle-ward stoutly yet keeping thcir ground: but the same stood in such danger, being now left naked on the sides, that the victorie must needes haue remained with the Danes, had not a renewal of the battell come in time, by the appointment (as is to be thought) of almightie God. ‘For as it chanced, there was in the next field at the same time an husbandman, with two of his sons busie about his worke, named Haie, a man strong and stiffe in making and shape of bodie, but indued with a valiant courage. This Haie beholding the king with the most part of the nobles, fighting with great valiaincie in the middle ward, now destitute of the wings, and in great danger to be oppressed by the great violence of his enimies, caught a plow-beame in his hand, and with the same exhorting his sonnes to doo the like, hasted towards the battell, there to die rather amonget other in defense of his countrie, than to remaine aliue after the discomfiture in miserable thraldome and bondage of the cruell and most vnmercifull enimies, There was neere to the place of the battell, a long lane fensed on the sides with ditches and walles made of turfe, through the which the Scots which fled were beaten downe by the enimies on heapes. ‘Here Haie with his sonnes, supposing they might best staie the flight, placed themselues ouerthwart the lane, beat them backe whome they met fleeing, and spared neither friend nor fo; but downe they went with all such as came within their reach, wherewith diuerse hardie personages cried vnto their fellowes to returne backe vnto the battell, for there was a new power of Scottishmen come to their succours, by whose aid the victorie might be easiile obteined of their most cruell aduersaries the Danes: therefore might they choose whether they would be slaine of their owne fellowes comming to their aid, or to returne againe to fight with the enimies. The Danes being here staied in the lane by the great valiainc of the father and the sonnes, thought verely there had beene some great sucors of Scots come to the aid of their King, and therevpon ceassing from further pursute, fled backe in great disorder vnto the other of their fellowes fighting with the middle ward of the Scots. . . But Haie, who in such wise (as is before mentioned) staied"
      ]
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "The Princess of this country, and the air on ’t",
      "notes": [
        "Country base] MURRAY (N. E. D., s. v. Base. sb²): A popular game among boys; it is played by two sides, who occupy contiguous ‘bases’ or ‘homes’; any player running out from his ‘base’ is chased by one of the opposite side, and, if caught, made a prisoner. [Present line quoted.]"
      ]
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "Revengingly enfeebles me; or could this carl,",
      "notes": [
        "Carle] MURRAY (N. E. D.)—[For the elaborate genesis of this word recourse"
      ]
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "A very drudge of nature’s, have subdued me",
      "notes": [
        "A very drudge of Natures] WALKER (Crit., ii, 309): In Rich. III: I, iii, we have ‘The slave of nature,’ which means neither more nor less than a born villain. [By quoting the present phrase immediately after his remark on Rich. III. the inference is that Walker would interpret it as a natural born drudge.]"
      ]
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "In my profession? Knighthoods and honors, borne",
      "notes": [
        "Lolling the Tongue] This forcible-feeble expression has not, to me, a Shakespearian stamp. Nor the use of ‘Tooles’ in the next line. The first line in all this description that, to me, gives the true ring is ‘To die with length’ned shame.’—ED."
      ]
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "As I wear mine, are titles but of scorn.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "If that thy gentry, Britain, go before",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "This lout as he exceeds our lords, the odds",
      "notes": []
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "Is that we scarce are men and you are gods.",
      "notes": [
        "deadmen] See WALKER (Crit., ii, 136), or II, iii, 77. 21, 22. deseru’d So long a breeding, as his white beard came to] WHITE: His service to his country made him worthy of the great age indicated"
      ]
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "[He exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "The battle continues. The Britons fly; Cymbeline is",
      "notes": [
        "Our Britaines hearts dye flying] THEOBALD: Thus all the editions, and thus Mr Pope in his [First] edition, most implicitly obsequious to nonsense. I corrected the passage in my Shakespeare Restor’d, as I have now reform’d it in the Text, and Mr Pope has follow’d my correction in his [Second] edition of our Author. [Theobald reads harts in his Text.]—INGLEBY (retaining ‘hearts’ of the Folios): Compare line 51, where the allusion is to the Romans’ hearts. The meaning is that the Britons were losing heart (courage); and flying, lest they should lose their lives; and they were thus putting their souls in jeopardy. [Is losing heart a commendable paraphrase of ‘hearts die’?—ED.]—CHURTON COLLINS (p. 303): Nothing could be happier than [Theobald’s] emendation of harts in this line. [Wherewith, I think, there will be general agreement.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "taken. Then enter, to his rescue, Belarius as Morgan,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "Guiderius as Polydor, and Arviragus as Cadwal.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan",
      "notes": []
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "Stand, stand! We have th’ advantage of the ground.",
      "notes": [
        "may saue But to looke backe in frowne: Stand, stand] That is, you may save yourself from this death that you shun by only making a stand and looking back defiance."
      ]
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "The lane is guarded. Nothing routs us but",
      "notes": [
        "by his beard.] SCHMIDT (Lex., s. v. Breeding): That is, who deserved to live so long as to breed his long white beard.—INGLEBY: That is, who shewed by his valour that he had profited by such long experience (in arms) as his long white beard cited.—DEIGHTON: Who, in so serving his country, well deserved of it the support it had given him during the life which his white beard showed him to have lived.—DOWDEN: Who deserved the nurture of his country for as many years as his white beard indicated. [May it not mean: Who, for this patriotic action, deserved as long a nurture in the future as his white beard indicated that he had been nurtured in the past? which differs but slightly from Dowden’s paraphrase.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "The villainy of our fears.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS, as Polydor, and ARVIRAGUS, as Cadwal  Stand, stand, and fight!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "[Enter Posthumus, and seconds the Britons. They rescue]",
      "notes": [
        "With faces fit for Maskes, etc.] DEIGHTON: With faces so delicate of complexion as to deserve masks to protect them from the sun, or rather, I should say, fairer than those by which masks are worn either for that purpose or to prevent impertinent curiosity; masks were commonly worn by ladies out of doors to preserve their complexions, or for purposes of concealment at theatres, etc."
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "Cymbeline and exit. Then enter Lucius, Iachimo, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "Imogen as Fidele.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "LUCIUS, to Fidele",
      "notes": [
        "not our men] THIRLBY (Letters to Theobald, in Nichols’s Illustrations, vol. ii, p. 229): What if we should read ‘her men’ instead of ‘our men,’ which is just"
      ]
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "Away, boy, from the troops, and save thyself,",
      "notes": [
        "To darknesse fleete soules that flye backwards] VAUGHAN (p. 515): This is not an imprecation; but, I apprehend, an aphorism, like the line preceding, and should be punctuated accordingly."
      ]
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "For friends kill friends, and the disorder’s such",
      "notes": [
        "Or we are Romans] That is, or else we shall turn Romans."
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "As war were hoodwinked.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "IACHIMO: ’Tis their fresh supplies.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: It is a day turned strangely. Or betimes",
      "notes": []
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "Let’s reinforce, or fly.",
      "notes": [
        "Let's re-inforce] CRAIGIE (N. E. D., s. v. 4.): To obtain reinforcements. [The present passage is the only one, except a quotation dated 1811, where this verb is used intransitively.]—DOWDEN: Mr Hart thinks that this means not obtain reinforcements, but 'renew the attack,' and he cites the Play of Shuckley (Simpson's School of Shakespeare, p. 207), where he believes the word bears this meaning. [The passage referred to is as follows: 'Retire thee into Clamagaboy Where Alexander and MacGilliam Buske May join their Scots. . . . And reinforce the English with fresh power,' where the word certainly seems to mean, as a footnote says, 'i. e., renew the attack upon, engage again'; and it is possible that it so means here, whether or not it is intransitive.—CRAIGIE (op. cit.) quotes a passage from Coriolanus as an illustration of the use of 'Reinforcement,' as meaning 'A renewal of force, a fresh assault'—'He \"aydelesse came off, And with a sudden re-inoforcement strucke Corioles like a Planet.\"—II, ii, 117.' Here again, as in Shuckley, it is transitive. It must, however, be borne in mind that these two examples are exceptions to the large number of instances involving the idea of added forces.—ED.]",
        "the File] MURRAY (N. E. D., s. v. sb2, II, 7. Mil.): The number of men constituting the depth from front to rear of a formation in line, etc.—SCHMIDT (Lex. 3): The number, multitude."
      ]
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "[They exit.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "ACT 5 SCENE 3": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Posthumus and a Briton Lord.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "LORD: Cam’st thou from where they made the stand?",
      "notes": [
        "Enter, etc.] KNIGHT holds that the minuteness of the stage directions in the first four Scenes of this Act savours of youth, and is possibly due to the fact that we here have the remnants of an early sketch which Shakespeare at a later period elaborated. [In Garrick’s Version the stage direction and opening lines are as follows: ‘A FIELD OF BATTLE. A grand Fight between the Romans and Britons: the Romans are drove off. Enter Posthumus and Iachimo fighting. Iachimo drops his Sword. Posthumus. Or yield thee, Roman, or thou dy’st. Iachimo. Peasant, behold my breast. Post. No, take thy life and mend it. [Exit Post.] Iachimo. The heaviness and sin,’ etc., etc., as in the original.—Ed.] 6, 7. and then leaues him] RUGGLES (p. 38): This mercy has a rich reward. Had Posthumus put Iachimo to death, he would have slain the only witness that could fully confirm Imogen’s truth."
      ]
    },
