    "88": {
      "play": "To Cymbeline performed.",
      "notes": [
        "to Cymbeline perform’d] COLLIER (ed. ii.): We think it likely that the whole of this part of Cymbeline was a quotation from some well-known and popular work on the same story. ‘Perform’d’ may there have been the rhyme to ‘adjourn’d’ and ‘turn’d’; but even if Shakespeare had himself been imitating that ballad-style of composition, he would hardly have been so lax in his writing. 98–118. THEOBALD: I own, to me, what Jupiter says to the Phantoms seems to carry the stamp of our Author, if the other parts of the masque appear inferior."
      ]
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "Then, Jupiter, thou king of gods,",
      "notes": []
    },
