    "184": {
      "play": "much drink; sorry that you have paid too much,",
      "notes": [
        "haue payed . . . are payed] STEEVENS: That is, sorry that you have paid too much out of your pocket, and sorry that you are paid, or subdued, too much by the liquor. So Falstaff: ‘with a thought, seven of the eleven I paid.’ —1 Hen. IV: II, iv, 213.—MALONE: See ‘he was paid for that,’ IV, ii, 318, above.—STAUNTON: ‘Paid’ is here equivalent to the slang phrase to settle, now in use, as ‘I’ve settled him,’ and the like. With this import, which is that of punished, ‘paid’ is often met with in old authors. [JOHNSON so failed to understand the opposition between the two ‘paids’ that he proposed: ‘And merry that you are paid so much.’ He took the second ‘paid’ to be paid, for appaid, filled, satiated. His note was omitted by MALONE in 1790 and in all subsequent editions, and charitably.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "185": {
