    "212": {
      "play": "should have the best use of eyes to see the way of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "213": {
      "play": "blindness! I am sure hanging’s the way of winking.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "214": {
      "play": "[Enter a Messenger.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "215": {
      "play": "MESSENGER: Knock off his manacles; bring your prisoner",
      "notes": []
    },
    "216": {
      "play": "to the King.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "217": {
      "play": "POSTHUMUS: Thou bring’st good news. I am called to be",
      "notes": []
    },
    "218": {
      "play": "made free.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "219": {
      "play": "JAILER: I’ll be hanged then.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "220": {
      "play": "He removes Posthumus’s chains.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "221": {
      "play": "POSTHUMUS: Thou shalt be then freer than a jailer. No",
      "notes": []
    },
    "222": {
      "play": "[bolts for the dead. All but the Jailer exit.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "223": {
      "play": "JAILER: Unless a man would marry a gallows and beget",
      "notes": []
    },
    "224": {
      "play": "young gibbets, I never saw one so prone. Yet, on my",
      "notes": [
        "prone] MURRAY (N. E. D. 7.): Ready in mind (for some action expressed or implied); eager. [Present passage quoted.] 208, 209. for all he be a Roman] ABBOTT (§ 154): ‘For’ in this sense [i. e., in spite of] is sometimes used as a conjunction, as here. That is, Despite that he be a Roman."
      ]
    },
    "225": {
      "play": "conscience, there are verier knaves desire to live,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "226": {
      "play": "for all he be a Roman; and there be some of them",
      "notes": [
        "some of them too] ‘Them’ is emphatic, as referring to the Romans, among whom, indifferent as they were to suicide, instances were found of a repugnance to death."
      ]
    },
    "227": {
      "play": "too that die against their wills. So should I, if I",
      "notes": []
    },
    "228": {
      "play": "were one. I would we were all of one mind, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "229": {
      "play": "one mind good. O, there were desolation of jailers",
      "notes": []
    },
    "230": {
      "play": "and gallowses! I speak against my present profit,",
      "notes": [
        "Galowses] That this is a vulgar pronunciation, as has been suggested, admits of doubt.—BRADLEY (N. E. D.): From the 16th century gallows has been (except the archaic a ‘pair of gallows’) used as a singular, with a new plural, gallowses; the latter, though perhaps not strictly obsolete, is now seldom used; 1562, Turner, Herbal, II, 46: ‘Mandrag. . . . grows not under gallosses.’"
      ]
    },
    "231": {
      "play": "but my wish hath a preferment in ’t.",
      "notes": [
        "a preferment] In spite of his pious and altruistic wish that all men might be of one good mind, the gaoler cannot quite close his eyes to the main chance, and so hastens to add that his wish includes some promotion for himself.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "232": {
      "play": "[He exits.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "ACT 5 SCENE 5": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Cymbeline, Belarius as Morgan, Guiderius as]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "Polydor, Arviragus as Cadwal, Pisanio, Attendants,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "and Lords.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE, to Morgan, Polydor, and Cadwal",
      "notes": []
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "Stand by my side, you whom the gods have made",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "Preservers of my throne. Woe is my heart",
      "notes": [
        "woe is my heart] See ABBOTT (§ 230) for ‘ungrammatical remnants of ancient usage.’"
      ]
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "That the poor soldier that so richly fought,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "Whose rags shamed gilded arms, whose naked breast",
      "notes": []
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "Stepped before targes of proof, cannot be found.",
      "notes": [
        "Targes] WALKER (Vers., 253): Palpably targe'. Targe in the singular would not be Elizabethan English. (Had Keats noticed this? Endymion, book iii: ‘Old rusted anchors, helmets, breast-plates large Of gone sea-warriors; brazen beaks and targe; Rudders, that for a hundred years had lost the sway of human hands.’)—COLLIER (ed. ii.): Possibly ‘targes’ is right; if so, it must be read in the time of a monosyllable.—VAUGHAN (p. 530): The point of the panegyric lies in this, that Posthumus with his naked breast was in advance of the whole rank of soldiers with shields; the loss of the plural ‘targes’ is not inconsiderable."
      ]
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "He shall be happy that can find him, if",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "Our grace can make him so.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  I never saw",
      "notes": []
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "Such noble fury in so poor a thing,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "Such precious deeds in one that promised naught",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "But beggary and poor looks.",
      "notes": [
        "But begger, and poore lookes] WARBURTON: But how can it be said that one whose ‘poor looks’ promise 'beggery,' promised ‘poor looks’ too? It was not the poor look which was promised; that was visible. We must read ‘poor luck.’ This sets the matter right, and makes Belarius speak sense and to the purpose. For there was the extraordinary thing; he promised nothing but poor luck, and yet performed all these wonders.—HEATH (p. 489): The sense is, one that promised nothing beyond what appeared, to wit, beggary and a poor exterior.—JOHNSON: To promise ‘nothing but poor looks’ may be to give no promise of"
      ]
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: No tidings of him?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "PISANIO: He hath been searched among the dead and living,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "But no trace of him.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE, to Morgan, Polydor, and Cadwal",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "To my grief, I am",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "The heir of his reward, which I will add",
      "notes": [
        "yet this] WHITE (ed. i.): The reading of the First Folio is in accordance with the usage of Shakespeare's time. [In his ed. ii. White abandoned 'the usage of Shakespeare's time,' and reads 'this yet.' Presumably by advice of his washer-woman, to whom, in difficult passages, as he states in his Preface, p. xii, he resorted.]"
      ]
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "To you, the liver, heart, and brain of Britain,",
      "notes": [
        "Liuer, Heart, and Braine] In Twelfth Night Orsino calls the ‘Liver, Braine, and Heart, These sovereign thrones,’ I, i, 128; not only because they are the seat of the passions, of judgement, and of sentiment, but they are also what was then considered the most vital organs."
      ]
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "By whom I grant she lives. ’Tis now the time",
      "notes": []
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "To ask of whence you are. Report it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "BELARIUS, as Morgan  Sir,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "In Cambria are we born, and gentlemen.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "Further to boast were neither true nor modest,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "Unless I add we are honest.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Bow your knees.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "They kneel. He taps their shoulders with his sword.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "Arise my knights o’ th’ battle. I create you",
      "notes": [
        "Knights o’th’Battell] Steevens: Thus in Stowe’s Chronicle, p. 164, edit. 1615: ‘Philip of France made Arthur Plantagenet, duke of Brytaine, Knight of the fields,’ [p. 244, ed. 1600]."
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "Companions to our person, and will fit you",
      "notes": [
        "With Dignities becomming your estates] Eccles: If, as seems probable, ‘estates’ was designed to express the rank which he had just raised them to, what are the ‘dignities’ yet to be conferred? ‘Estates becoming your dignities’"
      ]
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "With dignities becoming your estates. They rise.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "[Enter Cornelius and Ladies.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "There’s business in these faces. Why so sadly",
      "notes": []
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "Greet you our victory? You look like Romans,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "And not o’ th’ court of Britain.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "CORNELIUS: Hail, great king.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "To sour your happiness I must report",
      "notes": []
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "The Queen is dead.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Who worse than a physician",
      "notes": []
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "Would this report become? But I consider",
      "notes": []
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "By med’cine life may be prolonged, yet death",
      "notes": []
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "Will seize the doctor too. How ended she?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "CORNELIUS: With horror, madly dying, like her life,",
      "notes": [
        "With horror, madly dying, like her life] CAPELL (p. 120): A direct answer to Cymbeline’s question, ‘She ended with horror’; but the meaning of the words that come after, is—‘her death was mad like her life.’ [Those who indulge the fancy that there lies a similarity between this Play and Macbeth, find in the present passage and in Lady Macbeth’s death a confirmation thereof.]"
      ]
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "Which, being cruel to the world, concluded",
      "notes": []
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "Most cruel to herself. What she confessed",
      "notes": []
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "I will report, so please you. These her women",
      "notes": []
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "Can trip me if I err, who with wet cheeks",
      "notes": []
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "Were present when she finished.",
      "notes": [
        "she finish’d] INGLEBY thinks that this is equivalent to died, as on the strength of the use of ‘finish’ in line 490 of this scene. And he may be right, but it may also mean when she had finished her ‘confession.’ After a confession of abominable wickedness it is hardly likely that her women would wet their cheeks"
      ]
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Prithee, say.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "CORNELIUS: First, she confessed she never loved you, only",
      "notes": []
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "Affected greatness got by you, not you;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "Married your royalty, was wife to your place,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "Abhorred your person.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: She alone knew this,",
      "notes": [
        "She alone knew this] This was a truth so secret that only approaching death could have made her reveal it. Hence Cymbeline’s conviction that Cornelius is telling the truth.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "And but she spoke it dying, I would not",
      "notes": []
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "Believe her lips in opening it. Proceed.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "59": {
      "play": "CORNELIUS: Your daughter, whom she bore in hand to love",
      "notes": [
        "bore in hand] MURRAY (N. E. D., s. v. 3. c.): To profess, pretend; to lead (one) to believe. [The present line quoted.]"
      ]
    },
    "60": {
      "play": "With such integrity, she did confess",
      "notes": []
    },
    "61": {
      "play": "Was as a scorpion to her sight, whose life,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "62": {
      "play": "But that her flight prevented it, she had",
      "notes": [
        "preuented] Used passim in its Latin derivative sense."
      ]
    },
    "63": {
      "play": "Ta’en off by poison.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "64": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: O, most delicate fiend!",
      "notes": [
        "delicate] DOWDEN: I take this to mean ingenious here."
      ]
    },
    "65": {
      "play": "Who is ’t can read a woman? Is there more?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "66": {
      "play": "CORNELIUS: More, sir, and worse. She did confess she had",
      "notes": []
    },
    "67": {
      "play": "For you a mortal mineral which, being took,",
      "notes": [
        "mortall Minerall] MOVES (p. 53): This description is quite consistent with chronic poisoning by arsenic."
      ]
    },
    "68": {
      "play": "Should by the minute feed on life and, ling’ring,",
      "notes": [
        "and ling’ring] Both INGLEBY and VAUGHAN accept ‘ling’ring’ as transitive, with an objective you, either understood, or expressed after ‘waste.’—SCHMIDT and MURRAY furnish abundant examples from Shakespeare and elsewhere of ‘linger’ as a transitive verb; but is there any need of thus treating it in the present passage? As soon as the deadly mineral is taken, it begins to feed every minute on life, and then by lingering it wastes the victim by inches. It might feed on"
      ]
    },
    "69": {
      "play": "By inches waste you. In which time she purposed,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "70": {
      "play": "By watching, weeping, tendance, kissing, to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "71": {
      "play": "O’ercome you with her show and, in time,",
      "notes": [
        "and in time] WALKER (Crit., iii, 329): Perhaps, ‘and in due time.’ At any rate, yes is wrong.—DYCE (ed. ii.): The insertion of yes from the Second Folio, I confess, I hardly like.—VAUGHAN (p. 533): All change is unnecessary. ‘Now,’ ‘how’ and ‘show,’ and similar words are in Shakespeare di-syllabically pronounced by giving to ‘w’ the distinct enunciation of a syllable—thus, ‘nowu,’ ‘howu,’ ‘showu’—which they always possess more or less.—[I prefer the Yankee ‘haow,’ ‘naow’ myself—with a sharp nasal twang.—Ed.] 76–81. Heard you all this . . . like her seeming] STAUNTON (Athenæum, 14 June, 1873): The collocation and the metre in this pathetically tender lament"
      ]
    },
    "72": {
      "play": "When she had fitted you with her craft, to work",
      "notes": []
    },
    "73": {
      "play": "Her son into th’ adoption of the crown;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "74": {
      "play": "But failing of her end by his strange absence,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "75": {
      "play": "Grew shameless desperate; opened, in despite",
      "notes": []
    },
    "76": {
      "play": "Of heaven and men, her purposes; repented",
      "notes": []
    },
    "77": {
      "play": "The evils she hatched were not effected; so",
      "notes": []
    },
    "78": {
      "play": "Despairing died.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "79": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Heard you all this, her women?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "80": {
      "play": "LADIES: We did, so please your Highness.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "81": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Mine eyes",
      "notes": []
    },
    "82": {
      "play": "Were not in fault, for she was beautiful;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "83": {
      "play": "Mine ears that heard her flattery; nor my heart,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "84": {
      "play": "That thought her like her seeming. It had been vicious",
      "notes": []
    },
    "85": {
      "play": "To have mistrusted her. Yet, O my daughter,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "86": {
      "play": "That it was folly in me thou mayst say,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "87": {
      "play": "And prove it in thy feeling. Heaven mend all.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "88": {
      "play": "[Enter Lucius, Iachimo, Soothsayer, and other Roman]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "prisoners, Posthumus Leonatus behind, and Imogen",
      "notes": []
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "as Fidele, with Briton Soldiers as guards.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "91": {
      "play": "Thou com’st not, Caius, now for tribute. That",
      "notes": []
    },
    "92": {
      "play": "The Britons have razed out, though with the loss",
      "notes": []
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "Of many a bold one, whose kinsmen have made suit",
      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "That their good souls may be appeased with slaughter",
      "notes": []
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "Of you their captives, which ourself have granted.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "So think of your estate.",
      "notes": [
        "So thinke] See Text. Notes. THEOBALD was, I think, ill-advised in placing a comma after ‘So.’"
      ]
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: Consider, sir, the chance of war. The day",
      "notes": []
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "Was yours by accident. Had it gone with us,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "We should not, when the blood was cool, have",
      "notes": []
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "threatened",
      "notes": []
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "Our prisoners with the sword. But since the gods",
      "notes": []
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "Will have it thus, that nothing but our lives",
      "notes": []
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "May be called ransom, let it come. Sufficeth",
      "notes": []
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "A Roman with a Roman’s heart can suffer.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "Augustus lives to think on ’t; and so much",
      "notes": []
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "For my peculiar care. This one thing only",
      "notes": []
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "I will entreat: my boy, a Briton born,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "Let him be ransomed. Never master had",
      "notes": []
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "A page so kind, so duteous, diligent,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "So tender over his occasions, true,",
      "notes": [
        "So tender over his occasions] ECCLES: Respecting those matters to which it was the duty of his office to pay a particular care and attention. Possibly, it may signify, ‘over and above, or beyond what the duty of his place required of him.’—SCHMIDT (Lex., s. v. tender, 2. b.): That is, so nicely sensible of his wants. [‘So tender o’re’ occurs twice within six lines in Wint. Tale, II, iii, 160-5 of this edition, where I have erroneously asserted that the phrase is nowhere else used by Shakespeare, having unaccountably overlooked the present passage. I can plead no excuse, but solely beg forgiveness.—ED.]",
        "occasions, true] STAUNTON (Athenaeum, 14 June, 1873) would omit the comma, and explain as ‘his true occasions.’"
      ]
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "So feat, so nurselike. Let his virtue join",
      "notes": [
        "So feate] JOHNSON: That is, so dexterous in waiting.—BRADLEY (N. E. D., 2.): Of speech: apt, apropos; smart, adroit. Of movements: Dexterous, graceful. [Present line quoted.]"
      ]
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "With my request, which I’ll make bold your Highness",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "Cannot deny. He hath done no Briton harm,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "Though he have served a Roman. Save him, sir,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "And spare no blood beside.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: I have surely seen him.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "His favor is familiar to me.—Boy,",
      "notes": [
        "His favour] JOHNSON: I am acquainted with his countenance. 114, 115. I know not why, wherefore, To say] MALONE: I know not what should induce me to say live, boy.—DELIUS: Perhaps ‘to say’ refers not to what"
      ]
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "Thou hast looked thyself into my grace",
      "notes": []
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "And art mine own. I know not why, wherefore,",
      "notes": [
        "I know not why should say.]—VAUGHAN (p. 534): I would read as does the Folio, but with a different punctuation and meaning, thus: ‘And art mine own, I know not why: wherefore To say “live” boy ne’er thank thy master; live!’ With this meaning: ‘Thou hast by mere looking looked thyself into my favour, and art now mine own in some mysterious way, for which reason’ (wherefore) ‘thou needest not give to me, who am now thy master, any personal thanks for saying as I do, “Live!”’ . . . We have still the same form of construction in the common phrase ‘I will thank you to do this or that,’ etc., which means, ‘I will thank you for doing this if you do it.’—DOWDEN’s text reads: ‘And art mine own; I know not why; nor wherefore, To say, live, boy: ne’er thank thy master; live,’ and thus explains it: ‘I understand “I know not why” to refer to the preceding words, and “I know not” to be understood before “wherefore.” I take Lucius to be “thy master.”’ [This line the Globe ed. obelised, judiciously, I think. As it stands in the Folio it is certainly so obscure that it needs some emendation or, at least, change in punctuation.—PERRING (p. 452) accepts as correct the full stop after ‘mine own,’ and the omission of a connecting particle between ‘why’ and ‘wherefore’ as ‘worthy of admiration.’ ‘It just gives,’ he remarks, ‘that broken character to the king’s utterances which was natural to him under the circumstances; he stuttered and stammered while trying to recollect where and on what occasion he had seen the lad.’ Those editors who accept Rowe’s nor are generally silent, and leave the explanation of the Folio to those who follow it. Vaughan’s punctuation, in substituting a comma after ‘mine own’ instead of a full stop, seems to me good, but I cannot follow him in regarding ‘thy master’ as referring, not to Lucius, but to Cymbeline himself.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "To say “Live, boy.” Ne’er thank thy master. Live,",
      "notes": [
        "Neuer Master] ABBOTT (§ 84): By the omission of ‘a’ before ‘master,’ ‘never’ is emphasized and has its proper meaning, ‘at no time.’"
      ]
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "And ask of Cymbeline what boon thou wilt,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "Fitting my bounty and thy state, I’ll give it,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "Yea, though thou do demand a prisoner,",
      "notes": [
        "Yea, though thou do demand, etc.] CAPELL (p. 120): Here is a delicacy that deserves to be noted; the speaker wants some fit occasion to withdraw the promise he has made to his subjects, and spare Lucius, whose life, therefore, he indirectly puts the boy upon asking."
      ]
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "The noblest ta’en.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "IMOGEN, as Fidele  I humbly thank your Highness.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: I do not bid thee beg my life, good lad,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "And yet I know thou wilt.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "IMOGEN, as Fidele  No, no, alack,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "There’s other work in hand. I see a thing",
      "notes": []
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "Bitter to me as death. Your life, good master,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "Must shuffle for itself.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "LUCIUS: The boy disdains me,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "He leaves me, scorns me. Briefly die their joys",
      "notes": []
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "That place them on the truth of girls and boys.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "Why stands he so perplexed?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "Imogen stares at Iachimo.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: What would’st thou, boy?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "I love thee more and more. Think more and more",
      "notes": []
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "What’s best to ask. Know’st him thou look’st on?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "Speak.",
      "notes": []
    },
