    "267": {
      "play": "Italian fiend.—Ay me, most credulous fool,",
      "notes": [
        "Aye me, etc.] STAUNTON (Athenaeum, 14 June, 1873): Absurdly wrong. Read, unquestionably: ‘Give me,—most credulous fool, Egregious murderer, thief—anything That’s due to all the villains past, in being or To come!’—that is, ‘Give me any punishment that’s due,’ etc. The old spelling ‘Aye me’ in part, perhaps, led to the error. [Does not Staunton overlook the force of ‘anything’? Posthumus cannot find epithets vile enough wherewith to stigmatise his own conduct, and therefore says, in effect, ‘call me anything that would befit the very worst of villains.’—ED.]"
      ]
    },
