      "play": "Unlike than this thou tell’st. I lost my children.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "458": {
      "play": "If these be they, I know not how to wish",
      "notes": []
    },
    "459": {
      "play": "A pair of worthier sons.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "460": {
      "play": "BELARIUS: Be pleased awhile.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "461": {
      "play": "This gentleman whom I call Polydor,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "462": {
      "play": "Most worthy prince, as yours is true Guiderius;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "463": {
      "play": "This gentleman, my Cadwal, Arviragus,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "464": {
      "play": "Your younger princely son. He, sir, was lapped",
      "notes": []
    },
    "465": {
      "play": "In a most curious mantle, wrought by th’ hand",
      "notes": []
    },
    "466": {
      "play": "Of his queen mother, which for more probation",
      "notes": []
    },
    "467": {
      "play": "I can with ease produce.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "468": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Guiderius had",
      "notes": []
    },
    "469": {
      "play": "Upon his neck a mole, a sanguine star.",
      "notes": [
        "a Mole, a sanguine Starre] The COWDEN-CLARKES: Most poetically, as well as with a most subtle philosophical knowledge of Nature’s workings in the matter of kindred and inherited distinctive marks, has Shakespeare in this play given to the prince brother an almost precisely similar personal badge-spot with the one which lies upon the snow of the princess sister’s breast. Imogen’s ‘mole, cinque-spotted like the crimson drops i’ the bottom of a cowslip,’ and Guiderius’s ‘mole, a sanguine star,’ are twinned in beauty with a poet’s imagination and a naturalist’s truth."
      ]
    },
    "470": {
      "play": "It was a mark of wonder.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "471": {
      "play": "BELARIUS: This is he,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "472": {
      "play": "Who hath upon him still that natural stamp.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "473": {
      "play": "It was wise Nature’s end in the donation",
      "notes": []
    },
    "474": {
      "play": "To be his evidence now.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "475": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: O, what am I,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "476": {
      "play": "A mother to the birth of three? Ne’er mother",
      "notes": [
        "Nere Mother Reioyc’d deliuerance more] SCHMIDT (Lex., s. v. 2. trans. 6.) here defines ‘rejoice’ as ‘to be joyful at,’ but gives only one other example of a similar use: ‘which I in sufferance will heartily rejoice.’—Hen. V: II, ii, 159.—ONIONS gives the same definition with the same two examples.—ROLFE excellently obviates any forced meaning of ‘rejoice’ by considering ‘deliuerance’ as the subject and ‘Mother’ the object of the verb."
      ]
    },
    "477": {
      "play": "Rejoiced deliverance more.—Blest pray you be,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "478": {
      "play": "That after this strange starting from your orbs,",
      "notes": [
        "starting from your Orbes] This is generally explained as a reference to the Ptolemaic system, wherein the Sun and seven planets moved in concentric spheres, to which Shakespeare several times refers, and this may be the explanation. I incline to think, however, that ‘orb’ here means rank, station, coupled as it is with the assertion that the young princes are to return and again reign therein. For reference to the Ptolemaic system, see Ant. & Cleop., III, xiii, 175; Mer. of Venice, V, i, 74; Mid. N. Dream, II, i, 7, all of this edition, with notes thereon.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "479": {
      "play": "You may reign in them now.—O Imogen,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "480": {
      "play": "Thou hast lost by this a kingdom!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "481": {
      "play": "IMOGEN: No, my lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "482": {
      "play": "I have got two worlds by ’t.—O my gentle brothers,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "483": {
      "play": "Have we thus met? O, never say hereafter",
      "notes": []
    },
    "484": {
      "play": "But I am truest speaker. You called me “brother”",
      "notes": []
    },
    "485": {
      "play": "When I was but your sister; I you “brothers”",
      "notes": [
        "When we were so indeed] JOHNSON: If the Folio be right, we must give this speech to Arviragus.—WHITE: Possibly Rowe erred in making the change [from ‘we’ to ye]."
      ]
    },
    "486": {
      "play": "When we were so indeed.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "487": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE: Did you e’er meet?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "488": {
      "play": "ARVIRAGUS: Ay, my good lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "489": {
      "play": "GUIDERIUS: And at first meeting loved,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "490": {
      "play": "Continued so until we thought he died.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "491": {
      "play": "CORNELIUS: By the Queen’s dram she swallowed.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "492": {
      "play": "CYMBELINE, to Imogen  O, rare instinct!",
      "notes": [
        "O rare instinct] WALKER (Crit., iii, 330): Cannot ‘O’—sapins interpalatum—be dispensed with here? At any rate, we must pronounce instinct. Thus IV, ii, 229: ’Tis wonder That an invisible instinct should frame them To Royalty Vnlearn’d.’ 2 Hen. IV: I, i, 85: ‘He that but fears the thing he would not know Hath by instinct, knowledge from others’ eyes.’ Middleton and Rowley, Changeling, ed. Dyce, vol. iv, p. 289, [V, ii.], ‘O, but instinct is of a subtler strain!’ And so Milton, Par. Lost., x, 263: ‘By this new felt attraction and instinct.’ [It is strange that neither Walker nor his editor, Lettsom, noticed that, on the very passage quoted from this play, Malone’s note states that ‘the accent was laid on the second syllable of the word instinct.’—ED.] 457-459. This fierce abridgment ... rich in] GERVINUS (ii, 258, 4te Aufl.): Whatsoever might be regarded as somewhat capricious or arbitrary in the weaving of the outer circumstances of the plot is far counter-balanced by the inimitable dénouement in the last scene. This found favour in even Dr. Johnson’s eyes. It is so rich in its abridgement that verily the Poet seems to be praising himself for it in these lines."
      ]
    },
    "493": {
      "play": "When shall I hear all through? This fierce",
      "notes": [
        "fierce] JOHNSON: ‘Fierce’ is vehement, rapid."
      ]
    },
    "494": {
      "play": "abridgment",
      "notes": []
    },
    "495": {
      "play": "Hath to it circumstantial branches which",
      "notes": [
        "Distinction should be rich in] STEEVENS: That is, which ought to be rendered distinct by a liberal amplitude of narrative."
      ]
    },
    "496": {
      "play": "Distinction should be rich in. Where, how lived you?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "497": {
      "play": "And when came you to serve our Roman captive?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "498": {
      "play": "How parted with your brothers? How first met",
      "notes": []
    },
    "499": {
      "play": "them?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "500": {
      "play": "Why fled you from the court? And whither?",
      "notes": [
        "And whether these?] Here we have an example of THEOBALD’S clear vision in emendation, for which not one syllable of commendation did he receive from his successors who profited by it. His note is as follows: ‘The King is asking his Daughter how she lived since her elopement from the Court; when she entered herself in Lucius’s service; how she met her brothers, or parted from them; why she fled from the Court and to what place; and having enumerated so many particulars, he stops short, and cries, “All these circumstances, and the motives of Belarius, Guiderius, and Arviragus to the battle, together with a number more of occurrences by the bye, I want to be resolved in.”’ If Steevens had printed this note in full in the Variorum of 1778, MONCK MASON would have been spared the trouble of informing us (p. 377) who the ‘three were whose “motives” led them “to the battle.”’—ED."
      ]
    },
    "501": {
      "play": "To Belarius. These,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "502": {
      "play": "And your three motives to the battle, with",
      "notes": []
    },
    "503": {
      "play": "I know not how much more, should be demanded,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "504": {
      "play": "And all the other by-dependences",
      "notes": [
        "by-dependances] DOWDEN: Our word 'side-issues' comes near the meaning."
      ]
    },
    "505": {
      "play": "From chance to chance; but nor the time nor place",
      "notes": [
        "Interrogatories] TYRWHITT remarks that certain editors [see Text. Notes] have unnecessarily omitted ‘our’ in this line, inasmuch as ‘interrogatory’ is used by Shakespeare as a word of five syllables; see Mer. of Ven., ‘And charge us there upon intergatories,’ V, i, 325; again, two lines after: ‘Let it be so, the first intergatory,’ etc., where the First and Second Quartos spell it ‘intergatories.’ Again, in All's Well, ‘let me answer to the particular of the intergatories,’ IV, iii, 207. This spelling has been adopted by those editors who retain ‘our.’ See Text. Notes. 471, 472. the Counter-change Is severally in all] DEIGHTON: That is, each reciprocates the other’s joy."
      ]
    },
    "506": {
      "play": "Will serve our long interrogatories. See,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "507": {
      "play": "Posthumus anchors upon Imogen;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "508": {
      "play": "And she, like harmless lightning, throws her eye",
      "notes": []
    },
    "509": {
      "play": "On him, her brothers, me, her master, hitting",
      "notes": []
    },
    "510": {
      "play": "Each object with a joy; the counterchange",
      "notes": []
    },
    "511": {
      "play": "Is severally in all. Let’s quit this ground,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "512": {
      "play": "And smoke the temple with our sacrifices.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "513": {
